  "prompt": "Why is IBM's Lotus Notes still used so widely?",
  "response": "Lotus Notes (now known as HCL Notes) is still used widely in many large organizations for several reasons:\n\n1. Legacy systems\n- Many enterprises have deeply integrated Lotus Notes into their infrastructure\n- Migrating to a new system would be costly and complex\n- Existing workflows and databases are built around the platform\n\n2. Enterprise features\n- Robust email and collaboration capabilities\n- Strong security and encryption\n- Built-in document management and workflow tools\n- Support for complex business processes\n\n3. Backward compatibility\n- Supports older systems and databases\n- Allows organizations to maintain historical data and applications\n\n4. Compliance and regulatory requirements\n- Strong audit trails\n- Secure communication features\n- Meets many industry-specific compliance standards\n\n5. Custom application development\n- Allows organizations to create custom business applications\n- Low-code/no-code development environment\n- Extensive existing custom application base\n\n6. Long-term support\n- HCL Technologies (which acquired the product from IBM) continues to develop and support the platform\n- Regular updates and security patches\n\nWhile its popularity has declined, many large enterprises, particularly in finance, government, and healthcare, still rely on Lotus Notes due to these factors.",
